Once upon a time, there was a little girl who loved to read. She would read anything she could get her hands on, from picture books to chapter books to comic books. She would read in the car, on the bus, in the bathtub, and even under the covers with a flashlight.
One day, the little girl came across a book that changed her life. It was called "The Little Engine That Could," and it was about a little engine that was determined to pull a train full of toys over a mountain. The little engine was small and weak, but she was determined to try. She kept saying, "I think I can, I think I can," and she did.
The little girl was so inspired by this story that she decided to try to be more like the little engine. She started saying, "I think I can, I think I can," whenever she faced a challenge. And sure enough, she found that she could do things she never thought she could do before.
The little girl went on to become a successful woman, and she credits her success to the little engine who inspired her to believe in herself. She never forgot the power of those three simple words: "I think I can, I think I can."
The Little Engine That Could is a classic children's story that teaches the importance of determination and perseverance. The story follows a little engine who is determined to pull a train full of toys over a mountain, despite being told that she is too small and weak to do so. The little engine keeps saying, "I think I can, I think I can," and eventually she succeeds in her task.
The story is a great example of how determination and perseverance can help us achieve our goals, no matter how difficult they may seem. It also teaches us the importance of believing in ourselves and our abilities.
The Little Engine That Could is a timeless story that has been enjoyed by generations of children. It is a great way to teach children the importance of determination and perseverance, and to help them believe in themselves.

In a world where dreams are shared, a young girl named Yume sees a dream of a strange and beautiful world, unknowingly triggering a chain of events that will affect her and the entire world.
In the year 2015, a parasitic virus known as "Gastrea" infects humans and turns them into monsters. What is left of mankind now lives within the Monolith walls, walls that are made of Varanium, the only material that can hurt Gastrea. To counter the threat that the Gastrea pose, "Cursed Children"—female children whose bodies contain trace amounts of the virus—devote themselves to becoming demon hunters, battling the Gastrea in an effort to maintain the tenuous peace between mankind and the otherworldly invaders.
Misora Haruki, the new president of the biker gang "Hell's Wind," is also a Cursed Child, and just as she is pulled into the world of the demon hunters, she also finds herself becoming increasingly involved with the handsome demon hunter Kusanagi.
